  "response_text": "This is a comprehensive **Healthy Eating Plan** designed to be sustainable, flexible, and nutrient-dense. It is not a restrictive \"diet\" but a template for balanced eating that supports energy, weight management, and long-term health.\n\n### Core Principles (The \"Why\")\n\n1.  **Focus on Whole Foods:** Prioritize foods in their natural state (vegetables, fruits, lean proteins, whole grains).\n2.  **Balance Your Plate:** Aim for a visual balance of **Protein**, **Fiber (Veggies/Fruit)**, and **Complex Carbs** at every meal.\n3.  **Hydrate:** Water is crucial. Aim for 8+ glasses daily. Herbal tea counts.\n4.  **Mindful Eating:** Eat without distractions, chew slowly, and stop when you are 80% full.\n5.  **Consistency over Perfection:** One \"off\" meal doesn't ruin your progress. The goal is long-term habits, not short-term restriction.\n\n---\n\n### The \"Plate Method\" (For Every Meal)\n\nThis is the simplest way to build a healthy meal without counting calories.\n\n- **½ Plate:** **Non-Starchy Vegetables** (Broccoli, spinach, peppers, cauliflower, salad greens, asparagus, zucchini).\n- **¼ Plate:** **Lean Protein** (Chicken breast, fish, tofu, beans, lentils, eggs, Greek yogurt).\n- **¼ Plate:** **Complex Carbohydrates** (Quinoa, brown rice, sweet potato, whole-wheat pasta, oats, beans).\n- **Add:** A small amount of **Healthy Fat** (Avocado, olive oil, nuts, seeds).\n\n---\n\n### Sample 3-Day Meal Plan\n\n*Note: Portion sizes depend on your age, activity level, and goals (e.g., weight loss vs. muscle gain). Adjust accordingly.*\n\n#### Day 1\n\n- **Breakfast (7:30 AM):** **Greek Yogurt Power Bowl** (1 cup plain Greek yogurt, ½ cup berries, 2 tbsp chopped almonds, 1 tbsp chia seeds).\n- **Lunch (12:30 PM):** **Large Salad with Grilled Chicken** (Mixed greens, cucumber, tomatoes, bell peppers, 4 oz grilled chicken, ¼ avocado, 2 tbsp vinaigrette).\n- **Snack (4:00 PM):** 1 apple + 1 tbsp peanut butter.\n- **Dinner (7:00 PM):** **Baked Salmon** (4-5 oz) with **Roasted Broccoli and Quinoa** (½ cup cooked).\n\n#### Day 2\n\n- **Breakfast (8:00 AM):** **Oatmeal** (½ cup rolled oats, cooked with water or milk) topped with 1 sliced banana and a sprinkle of cinnamon.\n- **Lunch (1:00 PM):** **Lentil Soup** (1.5 cups, homemade or low-sodium) with a small side salad.\n- **Snack (4:30 PM):** 1 hard-boiled egg + 1 small carrot.\n- **Dinner (7:30 PM):** **Stir-fry** (4 oz tofu or shrimp, 2 cups mixed veggies like bell peppers, snap peas, bok choy) with ½ cup brown rice. Sauce: low-sodium soy sauce, ginger, garlic.\n\n#### Day 3\n\n- **Breakfast (7:00 AM):** **Veggie Scramble** (2 eggs scrambled with spinach, mushrooms, and onions) + 1 slice whole-wheat toast.\n- **Lunch (12:00 PM):** **Leftover Stir-fry** from Day 2.\n- **Snack (3:30 PM):** 1 cup mixed berries + a handful of walnuts.\n- **Dinner (6:30 PM):** **Turkey & Black Bean Bowl** (4 oz lean ground turkey, ½ cup black beans, ½ cup cooked brown rice, salsa, ¼ avocado, lettuce).\n\n---\n\n### Foods to Prioritize (The \"Green Light\" List)\n\n- **Vegetables:** All of them! Especially leafy greens, cruciferous (broccoli, cauliflower), and colorful ones.\n- **Fruits:** Berries, apples, citrus, bananas (in moderation).\n- **Proteins:** Chicken, turkey, fish (salmon, tuna, sardines), eggs, tofu, tempeh, legumes (lentils, chickpeas, beans).\n- **Whole Grains:** Oats, quinoa, brown rice, barley, whole-wheat bread/pasta.\n- **Healthy Fats:** Avocado, olive oil, nuts (almonds, walnuts), seeds (chia, flax, pumpkin).\n- **Dairy/Alternatives:** Plain Greek yogurt, cottage cheese, unsweetened almond/soy milk.\n- **Beverages:** Water, unsweetened tea, black coffee.\n\n### Foods to Limit (The \"Yellow Light\" List)\n\n- **Refined Grains:** White bread, white rice, regular pasta, sugary cereals.\n- **Added Sugars:** Soda, candy, pastries, sweetened yogurt, most granola bars.\n- **Processed Meats:** Bacon, sausage, deli meats (high in sodium and preservatives).\n- **Fried Foods:** French fries, fried chicken, chips.\n- **High-Calorie Drinks:** Juice, sweetened coffee drinks, alcohol.\n\n### Practical Tips for Success\n\n1.  **Meal Prep (Sunday):** Spend 1-2 hours chopping veggies, cooking a batch of quinoa or brown rice, grilling chicken, and portioning out snacks.\n2.  **The 80/20 Rule:** Aim to follow the plan 80% of the time. Allow for 20% to be flexible (a treat, a restaurant meal, a special occasion). This prevents burnout.\n3.  **Read Labels:** Look for items with **short ingredient lists** and avoid products with high added sugar (aim for <10g per serving for most items) or hydrogenated oils.\n4.  **Listen to Your Body:** This is a template. If you are hungrier one day, eat more vegetables and protein. If you are less hungry, eat less. Never force yourself to finish a plate.\n5.  **Don't Skip Meals:** This can lead to overeating later. Aim for 3 meals and 1-2 snacks, spaced 3-4 hours apart.\n\n### Sample Grocery List (To Get Started)\n\n- **Produce:** Spinach, broccoli, bell peppers, onions, garlic, lemons, berries, bananas, avocados.\n- **Protein:** Chicken breast, salmon, eggs, tofu, canned lentils/black beans.\n- **Pantry:** Rolled oats, quinoa, brown rice, olive oil, balsamic vinegar, peanut butter, almonds, chia seeds, low-sodium soy sauce.\n- **Dairy:** Plain Greek yogurt, unsweetened almond milk.\n\n**Before starting any new eating plan, it is always a good idea to consult with a doctor or registered dietitian, especially if you have a medical condition.**",
